1
00:04:33,280 --> 00:04:34,890
Would you look this way please?

2
00:04:35,650 --> 00:04:36,594
Okay!

3
00:04:55,365 --> 00:04:56,415
One moment.

4
00:04:59,965 --> 00:05:02,500
Mr. President, all systems activated.

5
00:05:02,662 --> 00:05:05,233
- I hope I didn't keep you waiting too long.
- Oh no, not at all.

6
00:05:05,290 --> 00:05:07,800
Congratulations Dr. Forbin.
It's a marvelous achievement.

7
00:05:07,897 --> 00:05:08,743
Thank you sir.

8
00:05:08,752 --> 00:05:10,528
- Hear, Hear!
- The limousine is ready for here.

9
00:05:12,516 --> 00:05:16,300
Of course it's gonna put me out of a job
and put the Pentagon in mothballs, but ah...

10
00:05:16,359 --> 00:05:19,024
- Congratulations Dr. Forbin.
- I'm quite sure that won't happen.

11
00:05:19,253 --> 00:05:21,600
Listen to him,
he's more relieved than anybody.

12
00:05:22,124 --> 00:05:26,100
Well the Secretary of Defense and
the Secretary of State and myself er...

13
00:05:26,177 --> 00:05:28,950
had a discussion on our way out here
and as to the treatment needed,

14
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:30,919
when we tell the country about it.

15
00:05:31,437 --> 00:05:32,670
And er...

16
00:05:33,163 --> 00:05:35,121
we all agree it should
be simple and direct.

17
00:05:35,151 --> 00:05:35,740
Yes.

18
00:05:35,789 --> 00:05:39,567
Downgrade the biggest top-secret
in all history, to plain unclassified.

19
00:05:39,817 --> 00:05:41,800
Now all we have to do
is tell the people about it.

20
00:05:42,647 --> 00:05:43,600
Thank you sir.

21
00:06:00,970 --> 00:06:02,060
My friends,

22
00:06:02,097 --> 00:06:03,945
fellow citizens of the world.

23
00:06:04,472 --> 00:06:07,017
For years we have been delicately
and desperately poised

24
00:06:07,161 --> 00:06:08,919
upon the brink of a disaster,

25
00:06:09,105 --> 00:06:11,774
too complete and horrible to contemplate.

26
00:06:12,188 --> 00:06:14,600
There is an old saying:
Everyone makes mistakes,

27
00:06:14,650 --> 00:06:17,085
but that is just
what man can no longer afford.

28
00:06:17,472 --> 00:06:20,609
For years, we here in the United States
have been working on that problem.

29
00:06:21,033 --> 00:06:23,802
Until now it's been our most
closely guarded secret,

30
00:06:24,077 --> 00:06:27,224
involving great effort,
and vast expenditure,

31
00:06:28,038 --> 00:06:29,892
but it has been met with success.

32
00:06:31,071 --> 00:06:33,229
As President of
the United States of America,

33
00:06:33,285 --> 00:06:35,900
I can now tell you,
the people of the entire world,

34
00:06:36,003 --> 00:06:38,500
that as of 3 AM eastern standard time,

35
00:06:38,761 --> 00:06:40,828
the defense of this nation,

36
00:06:40,900 --> 00:06:43,550
and with it, the defense of the free world,

37
00:06:43,659 --> 00:06:45,925
has been the responsibility of a machine.

38
00:06:47,296 --> 00:06:49,200
A system we call, Colossus.

39
00:06:50,407 --> 00:06:53,300
Far more advanced
than anything previously built.

40
00:06:53,786 --> 00:06:56,726
Capable of studying intelligence,
and data fed to it,

41
00:06:56,956 --> 00:06:59,000
and on the basis of those facts only,

42
00:06:59,155 --> 00:07:01,917
deciding if an attack
is about to be launched upon us.

43
00:07:02,470 --> 00:07:04,550
If it did decide
that an attack was imminent,

44
00:07:04,613 --> 00:07:06,300
Colossus would then act immediately,

45
00:07:06,350 --> 00:07:08,139
for it controls its own weapons,

46
00:07:08,335 --> 00:07:09,800
and can select and deliver,

47
00:07:09,884 --> 00:07:11,900
whatever it considers appropriate.

48
00:07:12,548 --> 00:07:16,300
Colossus' decisions are superior
to any we humans can make,

49
00:07:16,735 --> 00:07:19,114
for it can absorb
and process more knowledge

50
00:07:19,146 --> 00:07:22,500
than is remotely possible
for the greatest genius that ever lived.

51
00:07:23,601 --> 00:07:26,300
And even more important than that
it has no emotions,

52
00:07:26,429 --> 00:07:29,300
knows no fear, no hate, no envy.

53
00:07:29,670 --> 00:07:32,100
It cannot act in a sudden fit of temper.

54
00:07:32,497 --> 00:07:35,400
It cannot act at all,
so long as there is no threat.

55
00:07:36,123 --> 00:07:38,400
I would now like you to meet
Dr. Charles Forbin,

56
00:07:38,659 --> 00:07:40,964
the world's leading expert
on computer systems.

57
00:07:41,412 --> 00:07:42,650
And if you will,

58
00:07:42,700 --> 00:07:44,500
the father of Colossus.

59
00:07:46,409 --> 00:07:47,858
Thank you Mr. President.

60
00:07:48,356 --> 00:07:50,082
Ladies and gentlemen, I will...

61
00:07:50,238 --> 00:07:52,445
try to make this as simple as possible.

62
00:07:53,764 --> 00:07:58,027
The main memory and central processing units
are located here in the Rocky Mountains,

63
00:07:58,692 --> 00:08:01,400
inside this particular mountain,

64
00:08:01,730 --> 00:08:03,200
in Colorado.

65
00:08:03,739 --> 00:08:06,460
And overlooking the Pacific Ocean
in California,

66
00:08:07,185 --> 00:08:08,750
the Colossus programming office

67
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:11,800
oversees the entire operation.

68
00:08:13,200 --> 00:08:15,549
The... computer centre,

69
00:08:15,904 --> 00:08:20,241
contains over one hundred thousand remote
sensors and communication devices,

70
00:08:20,678 --> 00:08:22,111
which monitor all,

71
00:08:22,266 --> 00:08:25,804
electronic transmissions,
such as microwaves, laser,

72
00:08:26,143 --> 00:08:28,162
radio and television communications,

73
00:08:28,773 --> 00:08:30,900
data communications from satellites,

74
00:08:30,965 --> 00:08:32,390
in orbit all over the world.

75
00:08:33,311 --> 00:08:34,842
The entire system,

76
00:08:35,289 --> 00:08:38,334
is surrounded by fields
of intensified gamma radiation

77
00:08:38,360 --> 00:08:40,400
and other countermeasure devices.

78
00:08:41,866 --> 00:08:44,404
Colossus works completely
without human aid.

79
00:08:44,839 --> 00:08:46,469
We make no secret,

80
00:08:46,526 --> 00:08:48,500
of where Colossus is located,

81
00:08:48,982 --> 00:08:51,744
nor do we intend to conceal
how it functions.

82
00:08:52,670 --> 00:08:55,089
You may rightfully say that this
leaves us wide open to an attack

83
00:08:55,138 --> 00:08:58,213
frontally and subversively
and if that attack were successful,

84
00:08:58,551 --> 00:09:00,400
it would in effect leave us defenseless.

85
00:09:00,650 --> 00:09:01,749
However,

86
00:09:02,819 --> 00:09:05,600
Colossus does have its own defense.

87
00:09:06,650 --> 00:09:08,165
It is its own defense.

88
00:09:08,547 --> 00:09:10,669
In case of an attack,

89
00:09:10,739 --> 00:09:14,100
on any of its information supply
or power lines,

90
00:09:14,367 --> 00:09:16,400
Colossus will switch on
emergency circuits,

91
00:09:16,450 --> 00:09:19,110
which will then take
the appropriate action.

92
00:09:19,416 --> 00:09:22,239
It is... self-sufficient,

93
00:09:22,452 --> 00:09:23,861
self-protecting,

94
00:09:24,130 --> 00:09:25,621
self-generating.

95
00:09:26,541 --> 00:09:28,023
It is impenetrable.

96
00:09:29,115 --> 00:09:30,180
In short,

97
00:09:31,229 --> 00:09:35,161
there's no way in.
No human being can touch it.

98
00:09:36,565 --> 00:09:37,956
Over here...

99
00:09:39,914 --> 00:09:42,269
we have one of the many terminals,

100
00:09:42,651 --> 00:09:44,049
directly hooked,

101
00:09:44,435 --> 00:09:45,875
to the computer centre.

102
00:09:48,196 --> 00:09:49,540
Through this,

103
00:09:49,980 --> 00:09:51,715
Colossus can communicate with us,

104
00:09:52,814 --> 00:09:53,947
- excuse me gentlemen -

105
00:09:55,209 --> 00:09:56,900
and through this machine,

106
00:09:56,950 --> 00:09:59,656
we in turn can communicate with Colossus.

107
00:10:01,681 --> 00:10:03,350
Now there's one last point.

108
00:10:04,555 --> 00:10:06,632
One inevitable question,

109
00:10:07,196 --> 00:10:09,960
which we have been asked
very frequently before.

110
00:10:11,494 --> 00:10:12,643
And that is,

111
00:10:14,068 --> 00:10:17,663
is Colossus capable of creative thought?

112
00:10:19,990 --> 00:10:22,008
Can it initiate new thought?

113
00:10:23,777 --> 00:10:26,500
I can tell you
that the answer to that is No.

114
00:10:27,044 --> 00:10:30,166
However, Colossus is a paragon of knowledge,

115
00:10:30,200 --> 00:10:33,236
and its knowledge
can be expanded indefinitely.

116
00:10:34,780 --> 00:10:37,614
I hope, along with all the scientists who,

117
00:10:38,658 --> 00:10:40,902
helped make this particular project,

118
00:10:41,768 --> 00:10:45,041
that the immense power of this computer
will not only be used,

119
00:10:45,442 --> 00:10:47,233
for the defense of this country,

120
00:10:47,968 --> 00:10:52,464
but hopefully also as an aid to the solution
of the many problems that we face on this earth,

121
00:10:52,505 --> 00:10:54,982
and the many more problems
that we will face,

122
00:10:55,430 --> 00:10:58,129
the more deeply we penetrate
into the universe.

123
00:10:59,066 --> 00:11:00,068
Thank you.

124
00:11:00,100 --> 00:11:01,300
Mr. President.

125
00:11:02,765 --> 00:11:04,507
Thank you Dr. Forbin.

126
00:11:08,077 --> 00:11:09,127
And so,

127
00:11:09,755 --> 00:11:11,627
my fellow human beings,

128
00:11:12,423 --> 00:11:15,600
we all directly and
indirectly live in the shade,

129
00:11:15,648 --> 00:11:17,950
but not the shadow of Colossus.

130
00:11:18,922 --> 00:11:21,427
My sincere hope, is that now,

131
00:11:21,581 --> 00:11:24,955
we shall join hands and hearts
across this great globe,

132
00:11:25,433 --> 00:11:28,000
and pledge our time and our energies,

133
00:11:28,100 --> 00:11:29,700
to the elimination of war,

134
00:11:29,750 --> 00:11:32,928
elimination of famine, of suffering,

135
00:11:33,190 --> 00:11:36,630
and ultimately to the manifestation
of the human millennium.

136
00:11:37,303 --> 00:11:38,769
This can be done,

137
00:11:39,045 --> 00:11:41,222
but first there must be peace.

138
00:11:41,944 --> 00:11:42,995
Thank you.

139
00:11:55,812 --> 00:11:57,973
CPR Rec-Room, Blake Miller here.

140
00:11:58,233 --> 00:11:59,500
What?!

141
00:11:59,551 --> 00:12:01,074
Just a minute, I can't hear you.

142
00:12:01,259 --> 00:12:04,829
Hey, hold it down!
Hey, kill the noise, hold it.

143
00:12:04,940 --> 00:12:06,032
It's The White House.

144
00:12:07,618 --> 00:12:10,161
- Hello Charles.
- Hello Blake.

145
00:12:10,503 --> 00:12:11,619
How is everyone?

146
00:12:11,645 --> 00:12:13,900
- Everything's fine down here Charles.
- Very good.

147
00:12:13,950 --> 00:12:17,288
Dr. Forbin, we had a power failure
in one of the infra-red satellites.

148
00:12:17,314 --> 00:12:19,487
I can't, I can't quite hear you Dr. Markham.

149
00:12:19,602 --> 00:12:22,908
We had a power failure
in one of the infra-red satellites

150
00:12:22,934 --> 00:12:24,800
about an hour and a half ago,

151
00:12:24,889 --> 00:12:28,500
but Colossus switched immediately to the
backup system and didn't lose any data.

152
00:12:28,600 --> 00:12:29,721
So everything's fine now.

153
00:12:29,787 --> 00:12:32,500
Everything's been going so well,
we don't know what to do with ourselves.

154
00:12:32,560 --> 00:12:36,325
Out of desperation, Angela and I
have decided to get married.

155
00:12:39,089 --> 00:12:41,000
Finally, finally. Very good.

156
00:12:41,085 --> 00:12:42,470
Charlie, is that your crew on the phone?

157
00:12:42,496 --> 00:12:43,900
- Certainly is Mr. President.
- Can I talk to them?

158
00:12:44,007 --> 00:12:45,730
- Just go ahead sir.
- Blake, Hello!

159
00:12:46,001 --> 00:12:47,915
- Hello Mr. President.
- Hello everyone.

160
00:12:47,940 --> 00:12:50,017
- How are you?
- Are you having a good time?

161
00:12:50,043 --> 00:12:51,687
Yeah! Very good.

162
00:12:51,801 --> 00:12:52,787
Ahh, folks,

163
00:12:52,813 --> 00:12:54,473
I just wanna congratulate all of you,

164
00:12:54,660 --> 00:12:57,100
and wish all of you er... good luck
on your next projects.

165
00:12:57,172 --> 00:12:58,700
Thank you Mr. President.

166
00:12:58,890 --> 00:13:00,300
Have a good rest, you deserve it.

167
00:13:00,356 --> 00:13:02,000
- Thank you.
- We will!

168
00:13:02,474 --> 00:13:04,954
That looks like quite a party
you've got goin' there.

169
00:13:06,485 --> 00:13:07,800
Bye bye. Have fun.

170
00:13:07,879 --> 00:13:09,150
Here's Dr. Forbin again.

171
00:13:09,565 --> 00:13:11,814
How's the party down there Charles?

172
00:13:12,391 --> 00:13:14,015
I said, Charles,
how's the party at that end?

173
00:13:14,375 --> 00:13:15,657
I wish I could be
there with you

174
00:13:15,698 --> 00:13:18,400
because this party is becoming
a crashing bore.

175
00:13:25,114 --> 00:13:27,412
Please not that song, please not.

176
00:13:29,558 --> 00:13:32,550
Dr. Forbin,
send us a souvenir, will you?

177
00:13:32,600 --> 00:13:33,950
Say that again, what?!

178
00:13:34,391 --> 00:13:37,917
Steal us an ashtray
from The White House, OK?

179
00:13:38,330 --> 00:13:39,157
Very good.

180
00:13:39,765 --> 00:13:41,324
Goodbye.

181
00:13:43,578 --> 00:13:45,378
The President would like to say
a few words.

182
00:13:45,404 --> 00:13:46,574
Mr. President!

183
00:13:49,013 --> 00:13:52,132
Thank you Sam.
Has everybody had a drink?

184
00:13:53,298 --> 00:13:54,056
No?!

185
00:13:54,892 --> 00:13:56,727
Well, you get one, I'll wait for you.

186
00:13:57,963 --> 00:13:59,918
Harry Truman, years ago,

187
00:14:00,256 --> 00:14:04,002
when everybody was talking about,
passing the buck said that the buck stops right here

188
00:14:04,157 --> 00:14:07,081
- but now that's no longer true.
- Hear hear!

189
00:14:07,970 --> 00:14:09,543
Colossus will now take that buck.

190
00:14:09,954 --> 00:14:13,544
It will also have to take that
responsibility of a mega-million lives

191
00:14:13,570 --> 00:14:16,531
that all presidents
have had to carry since Roosevelt.

192
00:14:17,096 --> 00:14:20,103
And now, thanks to this wonder of science,

193
00:14:20,184 --> 00:14:21,276
Man no longer...

194
00:14:48,084 --> 00:14:50,104
Ladies and gentlemen,
may I have your attention please.

195
00:14:50,130 --> 00:14:52,410
Quiet, please, ladies and gentlemen.
May I have your attention!

196
00:14:52,437 --> 00:14:53,626
One moment.

197
00:14:53,960 --> 00:14:56,500
Everyone who's not Colossus cleared
must leave the room.

198
00:14:56,589 --> 00:14:57,738
I'm very sorry.

199
00:14:59,514 --> 00:15:01,616
My apologies.
Thank you, thank you very much.

200
00:15:10,313 --> 00:15:12,549
Is this a joke?
Is somebody putting me on?

201
00:15:12,582 --> 00:15:15,039
Sorry sir,
I can't hear a word you are saying.

202
00:15:15,953 --> 00:15:19,076
Would you be so kind as to have them stop
singing in the background?

203
00:15:19,116 --> 00:15:22,164
- What?
- Have them stop singing in the background.

204
00:15:22,213 --> 00:15:23,590
The music, oh I'm sorry.

205
00:15:24,298 --> 00:15:26,300
- Stop the music!
- One new, another system?

206
00:15:26,383 --> 00:15:28,444
I have no idea sir,
I'm … I'm just trying to find out.

207
00:15:29,104 --> 00:15:30,500
One moment, please.

208
00:15:30,595 --> 00:15:32,485
- Yes, Dr. Forbin.
- Doctor?

209
00:15:33,039 --> 00:15:35,842
There was just a message here
from Colossus in Washington DC.

210
00:15:35,915 --> 00:15:37,023
Can you explain that?

211
00:15:38,691 --> 00:15:41,100
- That's impossible.
- What do you mean a message?

212
00:15:41,160 --> 00:15:42,000
Everybody!

213
00:15:42,488 --> 00:15:44,836
Hold it, hold it a minute!
Guess what?

214
00:15:45,496 --> 00:15:47,400
There's a strange message on display.

215
00:15:48,494 --> 00:15:50,140
No ... no, wait a minute, I'm not kidding,

216
00:15:50,185 --> 00:15:52,800
it... it reads: There is another system.

217
00:15:52,850 --> 00:15:53,900
That's impossible.

218
00:15:53,949 --> 00:15:55,483
Could I have your attention please.

219
00:15:56,513 --> 00:15:58,369
Dr. Markham and the rest of you.

220
00:15:59,562 --> 00:16:02,900
Be so kind as to check the administrative
control programs right now.

221
00:16:02,950 --> 00:16:04,900
Just a moment. Mr. President?

222
00:16:04,946 --> 00:16:07,100
Soviet Ambassador, says it's urgent.

223
00:16:08,319 --> 00:16:10,538
Hello? Yes.

224
00:16:11,561 --> 00:16:13,631
What time do you call Mr. Ambassador?

225
00:16:14,584 --> 00:16:16,500
Oh yes we are, we are very proud.

226
00:16:18,793 --> 00:16:20,168
Repeat that again please.

227
00:16:22,507 --> 00:16:25,555
Yes I am.
Well, thank you for telling me in advance.

228
00:16:26,469 --> 00:16:27,716
No, no comment.

229
00:16:28,237 --> 00:16:29,483
Goodnight Mr. Ambassador.

230
00:16:29,923 --> 00:16:30,868
Goodnight.

231
00:16:31,138 --> 00:16:33,900
Dr. Fischer, run all the test programs.

232
00:16:33,941 --> 00:16:35,170
Get me Grauber.

233
00:16:35,227 --> 00:16:36,604
What's the CIA been doing?

234
00:16:40,384 --> 00:16:41,760
Well everyone, that's it.

235
00:16:41,812 --> 00:16:43,400
The supreme council of the U.S.S.R.

236
00:16:43,450 --> 00:16:46,400
has ordered as of 2300 hours
Moscow time tomorrow,

237
00:16:47,039 --> 00:16:51,300
the activation of an electronic brain,
exactly like ours, which they call Guardian,

238
00:16:51,413 --> 00:16:53,000
to be used solely for defense.

239
00:16:53,157 --> 00:16:55,700
My god, that's the other system.

240
00:17:01,449 --> 00:17:04,300
Ted, I want a complete rundown
on central intelligence,

241
00:17:04,349 --> 00:17:06,891
and no military moves to be carried out
without my personal orders.

242
00:17:06,917 --> 00:17:08,165
Yes, Mr. President.

243
00:17:08,947 --> 00:17:10,487
Charles, what do you think this means?

244
00:17:12,096 --> 00:17:13,800
To be quite frank with you, sir...

245
00:17:14,247 --> 00:17:16,000
I don't know, I'm not sure.

246
00:17:16,050 --> 00:17:18,720
Well, I am. It means
there's been a security leak.

247
00:17:20,199 --> 00:17:22,782
Sir, science is full of coincidences.

248
00:17:22,860 --> 00:17:24,473
Yes. Peterson! What's happening?

249
00:17:24,506 --> 00:17:25,792
They're still trying to find it.

250
00:17:25,995 --> 00:17:27,697
- Well have him paged.
- Hello Byron.

251
00:17:28,141 --> 00:17:30,397
You said we were years ahead
of the Russians.

252
00:17:30,470 --> 00:17:33,950
This was to be the race we won hands down,
without the splitting of one political hair.

253
00:17:34,016 --> 00:17:37,941
It was a hell of a shock, but we did
get there first, no-one can deny that.

254
00:17:38,009 --> 00:17:40,900
And there's one bright spot,
the way Colossus came up with the tip.

255
00:17:40,950 --> 00:17:43,500
I didn't realize
we'd be getting bonuses like that.

256
00:17:43,766 --> 00:17:45,200
Neither did I.

257
00:17:45,354 --> 00:17:46,176
What do you mean?

258
00:17:46,307 --> 00:17:48,100
I'm as surprised as you are, Sir.

259
00:17:48,180 --> 00:17:49,843
There's a spy there, Charlie.

260
00:17:50,111 --> 00:17:51,842
You've got a Russian agent in your crew.

261
00:17:52,670 --> 00:17:54,649
- Where is Grauber?
- He's coming Mr. President.

262
00:17:55,921 --> 00:17:57,300
Ok, well...

263
00:17:57,475 --> 00:17:59,500
What do you mean, surprised?
What kind of surprise?

264
00:17:59,757 --> 00:18:02,021
If we don't find any bugs in the system,

265
00:18:03,385 --> 00:18:05,300
it's built even better than we thought.

266
00:18:37,999 --> 00:18:39,350
Morning Charles!

267
00:18:42,333 --> 00:18:45,827
I cancelled all vacations,
put the entire crew on emergency.

268
00:18:46,210 --> 00:18:50,000
The ah... White House called
a defense group meeting,
for tomorrow morning.

269
00:18:50,368 --> 00:18:51,500
They wanna have you there.

270
00:18:51,557 --> 00:18:53,227
That leaves us very little time.

271
00:18:57,001 --> 00:19:00,606
Four hundred cycle powers of plasma
running at about, four percent disclosure.

272
00:19:00,701 --> 00:19:02,900
Good, that's well within
specification limits.

273
00:19:03,861 --> 00:19:07,800
I ran the communication subset
check-out program, it's perfect.

274
00:19:08,500 --> 00:19:11,100
So what do I do next,
I've tried everything I could think of.

275
00:19:11,193 --> 00:19:15,200
Well, try putting a dummy load on the system
and run it again, see if there're any changes.

276
00:19:18,430 --> 00:19:20,900
Maybe the system is overloaded, alright?

277
00:19:21,085 --> 00:19:22,128
Find anything at all?

278
00:19:22,168 --> 00:19:23,781
Nothing, everything checks out.

279
00:19:23,896 --> 00:19:25,110
Let me see this over here.

280
00:19:25,192 --> 00:19:27,000
Here are the results of the last test.

281
00:19:30,026 --> 00:19:32,112
And they check, here see?

282
00:19:32,266 --> 00:19:33,649
It's the same thing.

283
00:19:35,358 --> 00:19:36,190
Harrison...

284
00:19:40,034 --> 00:19:43,987
Check the perimeter bank and see if the reading
of any two produces a new third, alright?

285
00:19:44,931 --> 00:19:46,682
Dr. Fisher, thank you.

286
00:19:48,181 --> 00:19:49,101
Jeff...

287
00:19:50,420 --> 00:19:51,903
The console's feeling fine,

288
00:19:51,977 --> 00:19:53,247
hardware's healthy too.

289
00:19:54,633 --> 00:19:55,838
You're a big help.

290
00:19:56,899 --> 00:19:58,063
Miss Fields...

291
00:19:58,292 --> 00:20:01,208
May I suggest, Sir, that we first start,

292
00:20:01,347 --> 00:20:03,206
with the E-15-B test program?

293
00:20:03,285 --> 00:20:04,652
Er... no.

294
00:20:06,238 --> 00:20:09,634
Now let us run the ah... EC-13, right?

295
00:20:09,757 --> 00:20:11,183
It's two pages back.

296
00:20:12,462 --> 00:20:13,595
Lewis, any coffee?

297
00:20:13,806 --> 00:20:17,019
- I'll get you some Charles,
I'll get a cup myself.
- Thank you Blake.

298
00:20:17,163 --> 00:20:18,441
Ok, here we go.

299
00:20:22,832 --> 00:20:23,946
Attention...

300
00:20:26,896 --> 00:20:27,972
Program...

301
00:20:30,133 --> 00:20:31,729
EC-13.

302
00:20:33,913 --> 00:20:34,646
Run...

303
00:20:39,146 --> 00:20:40,580
How long does this usually take?

304
00:20:40,833 --> 00:20:44,200
Umm... over eleven hundred CPU seconds.

305
00:20:57,797 --> 00:21:00,000
Six point four five seconds,
what the hell is this?

306
00:21:09,805 --> 00:21:11,581
Communication with other system?

307
00:21:20,417 --> 00:21:22,100
Alright now, enough is enough.

308
00:21:23,566 --> 00:21:26,300
Which one of you jokers told
the system to display this message?

309
00:21:26,963 --> 00:21:27,802
Harrison?

310
00:21:27,982 --> 00:21:29,824
Not me, Dr. Forbin.

311
00:21:32,915 --> 00:21:37,200
Johnson, this sounds like your brand of humor,
you sure you didn't...

312
00:21:38,453 --> 00:21:41,540
Not me, not this time. Scouts honor, Pork.

313
00:21:42,119 --> 00:21:44,080
Operations, Fields speaking.

314
00:21:45,621 --> 00:21:47,304
Sir, it's the President.

315
00:21:51,599 --> 00:21:53,100
Yes Mr. President.

316
00:21:53,660 --> 00:21:54,833
What does this mean?

317
00:21:55,196 --> 00:21:59,000
Well it means Sir, that Colossus has requested
a communication link with the Soviet system.

318
00:21:59,067 --> 00:22:01,600
It's not a request, it's a direct order.

319
00:22:01,738 --> 00:22:04,000
You mean our computer wants to talk
to their computer?

320
00:22:04,050 --> 00:22:06,200
That is true Sir,
it wants to communicate with it.

321
00:22:06,317 --> 00:22:07,131
Why?

322
00:22:08,021 --> 00:22:10,082
You know as much about that as we do.

323
00:22:10,326 --> 00:22:12,300
We certainly never programmed that into it.

324
00:22:12,347 --> 00:22:15,500
If it's an order it either has to be
obeyed or ignored, doesn't it?

325
00:22:15,878 --> 00:22:16,754
That is right, Sir.

326
00:22:17,085 --> 00:22:18,527
What happens if we ignore it?

327
00:22:18,844 --> 00:22:22,020
If the computer is still operating
under our control, nothing.

328
00:22:22,141 --> 00:22:23,258
In other words...

329
00:22:23,607 --> 00:22:25,700
the order will simply remain
in the job stack,

330
00:22:25,762 --> 00:22:27,600
and will be repeated every half hour.

331
00:22:27,839 --> 00:22:30,470
IF the computer is still acting
under our control?!

332
00:22:31,367 --> 00:22:33,200
That is right sir, if.

333
00:22:35,616 --> 00:22:36,332
Alright.

334
00:22:37,009 --> 00:22:38,581
I see. Thanks Charlie.

335
00:23:15,885 --> 00:23:18,800
Well, at least the queuing programs
are still working right.

336
00:23:18,850 --> 00:23:20,481
Well, that's something anyway.

337
00:23:21,323 --> 00:23:22,284
OK now.

338
00:23:23,163 --> 00:23:26,564
Miss Fields, let's see if the executive programming
sections are functioning correctly.

339
00:23:32,095 --> 00:23:33,138
Attention...

340
00:23:33,798 --> 00:23:35,152
Message acknowledged.

341
00:23:50,314 --> 00:23:53,000
Facilities will not be made available
at this time.

342
00:23:54,013 --> 00:23:55,692
Do not repeat your request.

343
00:23:55,854 --> 00:23:57,474
End of message.

344
00:24:06,557 --> 00:24:07,559
Well,

345
00:24:08,414 --> 00:24:09,489
that's that.

346
00:24:11,323 --> 00:24:14,681
We'll know in about half an hour
whether we're still running the show or not.

347
00:24:28,306 --> 00:24:29,211
Well,

348
00:24:29,959 --> 00:24:31,279
we're still boss.

349
00:24:31,410 --> 00:24:32,452
Are we?

350
00:24:33,373 --> 00:24:34,919
Are you disappointed?

351
00:24:43,511 --> 00:24:48,364
The computational power of the computer
has increased about two-hundred fold.

352
00:24:48,936 --> 00:24:52,300
However, everything else
is functioning as expected,

353
00:24:52,713 --> 00:24:55,694
except for the...
heuristic programming section.

354
00:24:55,728 --> 00:24:58,728
I'm sorry to stop you again, Dr. Forbin,
but what exactly is that?

355
00:25:00,356 --> 00:25:03,892
That Sir, is the part of the computer
that simulates the human learning process,

356
00:25:04,775 --> 00:25:09,001
but so long as it is directed solely
to the execution of its problems,

357
00:25:09,964 --> 00:25:11,472
we have no complaints.

358
00:25:12,437 --> 00:25:15,343
- I guess that is, that is all.
- Alright.

359
00:25:16,713 --> 00:25:19,100
Mr. Grauber, let's talk about the CIA.

360
00:25:20,304 --> 00:25:24,196
Now, how is it possible your department
knew nothing about their system?

361
00:25:24,375 --> 00:25:26,900
- Mr. President.
- Ah... Charlie just...

362
00:25:27,014 --> 00:25:28,358
Dr. Forbin, just a sec.

363
00:25:28,888 --> 00:25:29,588
Well...

364
00:25:29,880 --> 00:25:31,256
Ah, Mr. President, excuse me but,

365
00:25:31,305 --> 00:25:35,713
Colossus has access to information
that wouldn't mean a damn thing to the CIA.

366
00:25:36,735 --> 00:25:41,528
Well I'm sure it's a marvelous machine,
Dr. Forbin, but ah, in all events,

367
00:25:41,747 --> 00:25:43,922
we do have agents, and eh...

368
00:25:44,352 --> 00:25:48,300
one of them did report on considerable
electronic activity in the, er...

369
00:25:48,370 --> 00:25:51,368
Krasny-Signorsk area of Siberia
about three years ago. Now...

370
00:25:51,408 --> 00:25:52,350
Mr. President.

371
00:25:52,408 --> 00:25:53,750
- We've been trying...
- Mr. Grauber,

372
00:25:53,800 --> 00:25:55,030
I don't care how you do it,

373
00:25:55,079 --> 00:25:56,741
I wanna know where
that thing is and what...

374
00:25:56,783 --> 00:25:58,355
- Mr. President.
- Charlie...

375
00:25:58,404 --> 00:26:00,407
I'm still presiding over this meeting.

376
00:26:00,904 --> 00:26:03,608
I... know that Sir, my apologies but...

377
00:26:05,522 --> 00:26:08,577
I do think that protocol wastes
an awful lot of time.

378
00:26:09,204 --> 00:26:10,883
I think all we have to do is,

379
00:26:11,610 --> 00:26:13,508
call the computer with this terminal,

380
00:26:14,029 --> 00:26:16,000
and we get the fastest possible answer.

381
00:26:17,803 --> 00:26:19,520
Alright, go ahead.

382
00:26:20,466 --> 00:26:21,581
Attention...

383
00:26:23,892 --> 00:26:25,600
Where is the other system?

384
00:26:31,537 --> 00:26:33,283
Bolshoi Olyania.

385
00:26:33,633 --> 00:26:35,521
So much for Krasny-Signorsk.

386
00:26:36,085 --> 00:26:39,001
Colonel, Bolshoi Olyania, O-l...

387
00:26:39,427 --> 00:26:42,393
O-l-y-a-n-i-a.
Look it up for me, will ya?

388
00:26:42,498 --> 00:26:44,537
- Yes sir!
- Peterson, situation room.

389
00:27:07,137 --> 00:27:09,907
Now Colonel,
where is Bolshoi Olyania?

390
00:27:12,360 --> 00:27:14,022
It's exactly...

391
00:27:14,234 --> 00:27:17,610
five miles south of Krasny-Signorsk, Sir.

392
00:27:19,415 --> 00:27:20,409
Thanks, Colonel.

393
00:27:24,131 --> 00:27:24,986
Alright.

394
00:27:26,950 --> 00:27:27,749
Now Charlie,

395
00:27:27,775 --> 00:27:30,468
what about this request
for transmitting facilities?

396
00:27:30,876 --> 00:27:33,344
Well Sir, we'll learn
a lot about the Soviet system

397
00:27:33,370 --> 00:27:35,666
if we set up exactly what Colossus wants.

398
00:27:35,845 --> 00:27:37,458
What do you mean?
Wh...what Colossus wants?

399
00:27:37,541 --> 00:27:40,173
Well, you see, it is built infinitely
better than we thought.

400
00:27:40,379 --> 00:27:42,668
It discovers there's another
system like itself,

401
00:27:43,336 --> 00:27:45,528
realizes that we don't know,
tells us about it,

402
00:27:45,553 --> 00:27:48,454
but knowing a little is not enough,
it wants to know more.

403
00:27:49,740 --> 00:27:52,574
What if Colossus starts transmitting
classified information?

404
00:27:52,853 --> 00:27:54,800
Then we would feed in a parameter

405
00:27:54,826 --> 00:27:57,684
to the effect that,
Guardian is potentially hostile

406
00:27:57,709 --> 00:27:59,989
and must not receive
classified information.

407
00:28:00,136 --> 00:28:02,230
Well what are we supposed to do Dr. Forbin?

408
00:28:02,393 --> 00:28:03,819
Eavesdrop on the line?

409
00:28:03,966 --> 00:28:07,105
Break the circuits
if Colossus starts spilling the beans?

410
00:28:07,372 --> 00:28:08,250
Exactly.

411
00:28:08,309 --> 00:28:09,547
Any objections Grauber?

412
00:28:12,182 --> 00:28:13,713
Well, I...

413
00:28:13,739 --> 00:28:15,130
I guess not sir.

414
00:28:16,092 --> 00:28:17,640
Anything else, Dr. Forbin?

415
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:20,982
Ahh, yes, Mr. President.
For the time being

416
00:28:21,008 --> 00:28:24,561
I should be the only one allowed
to communicate with the system because,

417
00:28:24,587 --> 00:28:27,347
Colossus deals in the exact
meaning of words

418
00:28:27,470 --> 00:28:30,251
and one must know precisely
what to ask for.

419
00:28:34,425 --> 00:28:35,482
Alright.

420
00:28:36,779 --> 00:28:37,813
Attention...

421
00:28:39,362 --> 00:28:42,228
Communications are being arranged
as requested.

422
00:28:43,582 --> 00:28:45,006
End of message.

423
00:29:08,317 --> 00:29:12,200
Video-scans are working properly, but
they could use a little phase synchronization.

424
00:29:12,309 --> 00:29:13,449
How long is it gonna take?

425
00:29:13,475 --> 00:29:14,887
We'll have it in no time.

426
00:29:23,264 --> 00:29:24,511
What the hell is that?

427
00:29:24,537 --> 00:29:26,200
It's a multiplication table.

428
00:29:26,556 --> 00:29:27,599
Thanks.

429
00:29:27,724 --> 00:29:32,300
Maybe, Colossus is trying to find a
common ground for communication.

430
00:29:44,144 --> 00:29:45,399
Operations centre.

431
00:29:46,890 --> 00:29:47,638
Sir...

432
00:29:47,973 --> 00:29:49,024
It's Grauber.

433
00:29:49,384 --> 00:29:50,337
Ohh...

434
00:29:54,525 --> 00:29:55,616
Hello Mr. Grauber.

435
00:29:55,787 --> 00:29:56,984
Hello Dr. Forbin.

436
00:29:57,326 --> 00:30:01,303
I was just wondering eh, is that what you
call a colossal sense of humor?

437
00:30:01,489 --> 00:30:03,941
The multiplication table isn't
classified this year, is it?

438
00:30:04,414 --> 00:30:05,473
Very funny.

439
00:30:05,499 --> 00:30:07,920
How long does your brainchild keep that up?

440
00:30:08,734 --> 00:30:10,127
Well, you see...

441
00:30:10,338 --> 00:30:12,496
it's much more interesting
when it starts dividing.

442
00:30:13,793 --> 00:30:15,184
Yeah, I can hardly wait.

443
00:30:15,974 --> 00:30:18,605
I suppose know you the Russian machine
has been activated.

444
00:30:19,013 --> 00:30:20,837
We got a quick rundown on it.

445
00:30:20,961 --> 00:30:24,613
It's similar to Colossus in layout,
but it's not concentrated in one area.

446
00:30:24,700 --> 00:30:25,500
Oh?

447
00:30:27,513 --> 00:30:31,540
But Colossus must be sending it back to school,
the Russians must absolutely furious about that.

448
00:30:32,509 --> 00:30:34,063
Well I'm glad you're in such a good mood.

449
00:30:36,126 --> 00:30:38,434
- I'll call you back later.
- Yes, thank you.

450
00:30:47,754 --> 00:30:49,024
This is incredible.

451
00:30:49,081 --> 00:30:49,799
What?

452
00:30:50,092 --> 00:30:51,143
Something wrong?

453
00:30:52,157 --> 00:30:55,809
- Well it's good, sound calculus, but...
- But what?

454
00:30:58,767 --> 00:30:59,834
It's different.

455
00:31:00,209 --> 00:31:01,186
How?

456
00:31:01,863 --> 00:31:02,921
Take a look at it.

457
00:31:05,083 --> 00:31:08,963
From the multiplication tables
to calculus in less than an hour.

458
00:31:09,008 --> 00:31:10,900
God only knows where it'll be by morning.

459
00:31:10,950 --> 00:31:14,502
It's like five years of Cal-tech
in fifteen seconds.

460
00:31:14,705 --> 00:31:17,481
It's beyond comprehension.
I don't like to think about it.

461
00:31:17,976 --> 00:31:19,027
Take a look.

462
00:31:19,597 --> 00:31:22,565
Going so fast, the entire system
could break down.

463
00:31:23,939 --> 00:31:25,832
Alright, let's see what's up there now.

464
00:31:26,634 --> 00:31:28,158
Harrison, dump the terminals buffer,

465
00:31:28,184 --> 00:31:31,175
and print what's being transmitted
at this moment, alright?

466
00:32:01,912 --> 00:32:03,038
What is it Charles?

467
00:32:04,372 --> 00:32:06,766
This is way beyond me.

468
00:32:07,346 --> 00:32:09,479
This thing is deep in finite absolutes.

469
00:32:09,644 --> 00:32:12,940
Well, it's certainly beyond the knowledge
of any human being.

470
00:32:13,163 --> 00:32:15,265
- No, it's not.
- Isn't it?

471
00:32:15,778 --> 00:32:17,537
No, because whatever it is...

472
00:32:18,735 --> 00:32:19,900
we can go back...

473
00:32:21,635 --> 00:32:24,030
and analyze this whole printout in detail.

474
00:32:25,493 --> 00:32:28,450
This might very well
become new knowledge for mankind.

475
00:33:00,506 --> 00:33:02,400
Operations centre, Fields speaking.

476
00:33:02,560 --> 00:33:03,829
But just a moment...

477
00:33:03,937 --> 00:33:05,355
It's The White House.

478
00:33:13,130 --> 00:33:14,134
Yes, Mr. President.

479
00:33:14,184 --> 00:33:15,923
Charlie, what's going on?

480
00:33:16,232 --> 00:33:18,458
Well apparently Colossus and
Guardian are establishing

481
00:33:18,484 --> 00:33:20,606
a common basis
for communication. They...

482
00:33:20,818 --> 00:33:22,907
started right at the beginning
with the multiplication table.

483
00:33:22,984 --> 00:33:24,328
Well, what are they up to?

484
00:33:24,580 --> 00:33:26,820
I don't know Sir,
but it's, it's quite incredible.

485
00:33:27,153 --> 00:33:30,649
Just the, few hours that we have spent
studying the Colossus printout,

486
00:33:31,340 --> 00:33:33,515
we have found a new statement in gravitation,

487
00:33:34,134 --> 00:33:37,250
and a confirmation of the Eddington theory
of the expanding universe.

488
00:33:37,300 --> 00:33:42,200
It... seems as if science is advancing hundreds
of years within a matter of seconds.

489
00:33:42,791 --> 00:33:45,963
It's... quite fantastic, just take a look at it.

490
00:34:12,986 --> 00:34:15,800
It started slowing down
fifteen minutes ago.

491
00:34:15,850 --> 00:34:17,904
It's speed has been reduced
by ninety percent.

492
00:34:18,210 --> 00:34:19,928
Has there been a hardware failure?

493
00:34:20,108 --> 00:34:22,500
No. Our field engineers can't find one.

494
00:34:22,587 --> 00:34:24,160
It's just waiting.

495
00:34:24,852 --> 00:34:25,822
Waiting?

496
00:34:25,871 --> 00:34:27,467
For Guardian to catch up with it.

497
00:34:31,582 --> 00:34:33,227
Almost there...

498
00:34:34,270 --> 00:34:36,100
Right now, they're synchronized.

499
00:35:03,063 --> 00:35:04,090
Now what?

500
00:35:04,253 --> 00:35:05,279
They've stopped.

501
00:35:06,031 --> 00:35:08,377
Yes, Charles.
I can see that it stopped.

502
00:35:08,539 --> 00:35:10,901
What the hell does it mean?
Have they broken down or something?

503
00:35:11,042 --> 00:35:11,963
Is it all over?

504
00:35:12,109 --> 00:35:13,461
I'll ask, Blake...

505
00:35:13,568 --> 00:35:14,723
Attention.

506
00:35:17,316 --> 00:35:18,391
Status!

507
00:35:46,314 --> 00:35:47,500
Well, there it is.

508
00:35:48,416 --> 00:35:51,226
There's the common basis
for communication.

509
00:35:51,536 --> 00:35:52,790
A new language.

510
00:35:53,392 --> 00:35:55,176
An inter-system language.

511
00:35:58,019 --> 00:36:00,963
A language only those
machines can understand.

512
00:36:07,601 --> 00:36:10,738
Peterson, what's the delay with the call
to Moscow? I've waited long enough.

513
00:36:11,151 --> 00:36:12,617
It's coming on now, Mr. President.

514
00:36:15,932 --> 00:36:17,700
Morning, Mr. President.

515
00:36:17,757 --> 00:36:19,200
Good evening Mr. Chairman.

516
00:36:19,524 --> 00:36:20,867
I'm sorry.

517
00:36:28,259 --> 00:36:30,200
And sorry to have kept you waiting.

518
00:36:30,328 --> 00:36:32,700
Oh, you didn't Mr. Chairman,
I just got here myself.

519
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:36,600
Ohh, I am understand English,
but I cannot speak.

520
00:36:39,293 --> 00:36:41,340
I will get instantly to the point.

521
00:36:43,122 --> 00:36:44,539
My advisers tell me...

522
00:36:45,247 --> 00:36:46,323
that Colossus...

523
00:36:47,242 --> 00:36:48,366
and Guardian...

524
00:36:48,651 --> 00:36:51,282
are now exchanging data...

525
00:36:51,892 --> 00:36:53,513
which our experts...

526
00:36:53,791 --> 00:36:55,300
do not understand.

527
00:36:56,291 --> 00:36:58,738
The matter... is made...

528
00:36:58,843 --> 00:36:59,933
more serious...

529
00:37:01,628 --> 00:37:04,873
by the sudden increase in...
transmission.

530
00:37:06,551 --> 00:37:08,775
At this speed
we cannot determine...

531
00:37:09,479 --> 00:37:11,352
what our machines may reveal...

532
00:37:14,033 --> 00:37:15,800
of our defenses.

533
00:37:17,956 --> 00:37:21,585
You can appreciate...
that you are also...

534
00:37:23,682 --> 00:37:25,691
in exactly the same...

535
00:37:26,131 --> 00:37:27,723
s...situation.

536
00:37:31,218 --> 00:37:32,089
Alright.

537
00:37:32,392 --> 00:37:35,600
We'll stop both machines as soon as
our experts can arrange a time.

538
00:37:35,747 --> 00:37:37,659
Both to go off at the same time.

539
00:37:37,759 --> 00:37:39,759
And neither to be switched on
for transmission,

540
00:37:39,837 --> 00:37:43,301
without prior agreement or at least,
consultation with the other.

541
00:37:48,374 --> 00:37:49,946
Very well, Mr. President.

542
00:37:53,385 --> 00:37:55,970
I congratulate you
on your speedy decision.

543
00:37:57,716 --> 00:38:00,500
When can you have your expert
available on this line?

544
00:38:00,600 --> 00:38:01,764
In a couple of hours.

545
00:38:03,616 --> 00:38:05,335
That will be excellent.

546
00:38:06,368 --> 00:38:08,146
I will have our man waiting.

547
00:38:11,824 --> 00:38:13,700
Thank you very much
Mr. President

548
00:38:14,040 --> 00:38:15,600
for your cooperation.

549
00:38:15,661 --> 00:38:17,635
Thank you for yours, Mr. Chairman.

550
00:38:18,875 --> 00:38:20,349
Peterson, get me Forbin.

551
00:38:45,320 --> 00:38:48,103
Is that your... final decision Sir?

552
00:38:49,336 --> 00:38:50,902
That's the way I'm going to have it.

553
00:38:51,822 --> 00:38:54,057
Mr. President, to be quite frank with you...

554
00:38:54,751 --> 00:38:58,059
I think that you will change your mind
if you finally realize that this is...

555
00:38:58,857 --> 00:39:01,831
more than just a souped-up adding machine.

556
00:39:02,067 --> 00:39:03,156
Excuse me, Mr. President.

557
00:39:03,522 --> 00:39:04,879
Moscow on the line.

558
00:39:05,641 --> 00:39:07,719
Throw it on these monitors
out here please.

559
00:39:12,625 --> 00:39:13,814
Hello Mr. Chairman.

560
00:39:15,951 --> 00:39:17,262
This is Dr. Forbin.

561
00:39:28,648 --> 00:39:30,303
Hello Dr. Kuprin, how are you?

562
00:39:30,429 --> 00:39:34,920
I prefer to not use a translator
if you don't mind my English.

563
00:39:35,404 --> 00:39:37,353
It has to be better than my Russian.

564
00:39:37,710 --> 00:39:39,696
You are too modest Dr. Forbin.

565
00:39:40,553 --> 00:39:44,085
As you probably know I've been ordered
to break the communication lines.

566
00:39:44,644 --> 00:39:48,200
So have I, I... don't approve
of handling the situation this way.

567
00:39:49,246 --> 00:39:52,969
Neither do I but how do you propose
we do what we've been ordered to do?

568
00:39:53,246 --> 00:39:54,938
There's not much choice is there?

569
00:39:55,388 --> 00:39:57,600
Dropping the lines
could be very dangerous.

570
00:39:57,650 --> 00:39:58,300
Exactly.

571
00:39:58,400 --> 00:40:02,424
I... think we just have to hope that
the two machines aren't too disappointed.

572
00:40:02,552 --> 00:40:04,674
We understand each other perfectly.

573
00:40:04,939 --> 00:40:07,250
We can be ready in exactly fifteen minutes.

574
00:40:08,085 --> 00:40:09,436
Good luck Doctor.

575
00:40:09,470 --> 00:40:10,626
And to you.

576
00:40:11,172 --> 00:40:12,000
Thank you.

577
00:40:12,239 --> 00:40:16,913
Mr. Chairman, Dr. Kuprin. I suggest
we keep our lines open and stand-by.

578
00:40:22,246 --> 00:40:23,028
Six...

579
00:40:23,925 --> 00:40:24,576
Five...

580
00:40:25,415 --> 00:40:25,953
Four...

581
00:40:27,028 --> 00:40:27,712
Three...

582
00:40:28,568 --> 00:40:29,138
Two...

583
00:40:30,162 --> 00:40:30,814
One...

584
00:40:31,279 --> 00:40:32,224
Now.

585
00:40:36,635 --> 00:40:37,934
That's that.

586
00:40:54,879 --> 00:40:55,857
What's it doing?

587
00:40:56,866 --> 00:40:59,028
It's trying to find an alternate route.

588
00:41:06,952 --> 00:41:08,914
Persistent devil isn't he?

589
00:41:09,577 --> 00:41:10,343
It...

590
00:41:10,399 --> 00:41:11,401
I mean it.

591
00:41:11,777 --> 00:41:13,349
Don't personalize it Grauber.

592
00:41:14,302 --> 00:41:15,931
The next stop is deification.

593
00:41:27,300 --> 00:41:29,609
- Call for the systems' attention.
- What are you doing?

594
00:41:29,850 --> 00:41:33,062
I'm going to answer it if it's,
alright with you Sir.

595
00:41:35,856 --> 00:41:37,035
Attention...

596
00:41:40,303 --> 00:41:41,774
Message acknowledged.

597
00:41:49,332 --> 00:41:51,485
- Mr. President?
- Tell it the truth.

598
00:41:54,893 --> 00:41:56,725
Communication broken...

599
00:41:57,362 --> 00:41:58,625
on presidential order.

600
00:42:06,955 --> 00:42:09,565
You two have a big decision
to make, Mr. President.

601
00:42:11,433 --> 00:42:14,097
No, I agree with you Mr. President.

602
00:42:15,130 --> 00:42:17,842
The machines... are very clever,

603
00:42:18,344 --> 00:42:21,300
...and regardless of their nationalities,

604
00:42:21,374 --> 00:42:24,920
they must learn, that man is the master.

605
00:42:24,983 --> 00:42:26,223
Exactly.

606
00:42:26,712 --> 00:42:30,255
Gentlemen, excuse me but I... I honestly
don't think you're being very realistic,

607
00:42:30,281 --> 00:42:32,137
I think you'd better reconsider.

608
00:42:33,925 --> 00:42:35,416
Don't you agree Dr. Kuprin?

609
00:42:35,529 --> 00:42:37,744
I certainly do Dr. Forbin.

610
00:42:44,457 --> 00:42:45,816
Dr. Forbin.

611
00:42:48,038 --> 00:42:50,148
If we give way now,

612
00:42:50,507 --> 00:42:56,602
it will be ten times, twenty times harder,
to take a firm stand later on.

613
00:42:57,379 --> 00:42:59,137
The decision is made.

614
00:42:59,158 --> 00:42:59,981
Right.

615
00:43:00,860 --> 00:43:02,550
No matter what our differences are,

616
00:43:02,655 --> 00:43:04,614
Man is man, that's it.

617
00:43:04,700 --> 00:43:06,083
Dr. Forbin.

618
00:43:10,944 --> 00:43:12,173
Attention...

619
00:43:14,794 --> 00:43:17,404
By order of The President of
The United States of America,

620
00:43:17,676 --> 00:43:19,451
The Chairman of The U.S.S.R.,

621
00:43:20,608 --> 00:43:23,283
communications will not be restored
at this time.

622
00:43:24,281 --> 00:43:25,568
End of message.

623
00:43:31,547 --> 00:43:33,953
Ah you have to give it an E for effort.

624
00:43:44,035 --> 00:43:46,653
- "Action will be taken!"
- What kind of action?

625
00:43:46,984 --> 00:43:48,657
What kind of action?

626
00:43:52,503 --> 00:43:53,887
What kind of action?

627
00:43:58,825 --> 00:44:00,071
Why doesn't it answer?

628
00:44:01,635 --> 00:44:03,545
Report propose action.

629
00:44:04,441 --> 00:44:07,230
It lost control Forbin,
it's not listening to you.

630
00:44:09,208 --> 00:44:10,952
Acknowledge the last message please.

631
00:44:16,485 --> 00:44:19,810
Mr. President, the executive programming
unit refuses to function.

632
00:44:19,931 --> 00:44:22,108
I think you two better change your minds.

633
00:44:25,160 --> 00:44:27,825
Peterson, throw the Moscow call
on the large monitor.

634
00:44:33,654 --> 00:44:34,542
Send what I tell you.

635
00:44:34,689 --> 00:44:35,746
Attention...

636
00:44:37,523 --> 00:44:39,914
This is The President of
The United States of America.

637
00:44:40,212 --> 00:44:41,669
We will not be threatened.

638
00:44:42,134 --> 00:44:43,812
You will obey your superiors.

639
00:44:44,424 --> 00:44:47,200
Transmitting facilities
will not be re-instated.

640
00:45:02,639 --> 00:45:03,670
Oh my god!

641
00:45:05,722 --> 00:45:07,099
Dr. Kuprin. Kuprin!

642
00:45:07,125 --> 00:45:08,150
Yes Dr. Forbin.

643
00:45:08,200 --> 00:45:09,673
A missile has just been launched.

644
00:45:09,699 --> 00:45:13,360
It is heading towards
the Sayan-Sibirsk oil complex.

645
00:45:32,906 --> 00:45:34,350
Mr. President.

646
00:45:34,400 --> 00:45:35,123
Yes.

647
00:45:36,753 --> 00:45:38,625
Guardian has retaliated.

648
00:45:38,677 --> 00:45:39,989
Retaliated?

649
00:45:40,029 --> 00:45:41,177
Yes, Mr. President.

650
00:45:41,203 --> 00:45:42,521
A missile has been launched.

651
00:45:42,823 --> 00:45:45,000
Target: Henderson Air Force Base,

652
00:45:45,100 --> 00:45:46,621
Henderson, Texas.

653
00:45:49,644 --> 00:45:52,143
Mr. President, we have both
missiles on the radar screen.

654
00:45:53,214 --> 00:45:55,121
Forbin, tell Colossus...

655
00:45:55,755 --> 00:45:59,100
- Charlie, tell Colossus...
- Yes Mr. President I know,
but it may be, it may be too late Sir.

656
00:45:59,150 --> 00:46:00,633
Get the Texan Governor.

657
00:46:01,426 --> 00:46:03,918
Forbin! Guardian does not respond.

658
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:05,939
The two machines are working together.

659
00:46:07,145 --> 00:46:07,894
Attention...

660
00:46:08,290 --> 00:46:10,717
Use anti-missile missile
to intercept Soviet missile.

661
00:46:10,776 --> 00:46:12,120
Acknowledge message.

662
00:46:20,418 --> 00:46:23,350
Mr. President, we have got less than thirty
seconds to re-establish the communications.

663
00:46:23,400 --> 00:46:25,230
What are you waiting for?
Restore them, hurry!

664
00:46:25,727 --> 00:46:27,750
Peterson, call up operations immediately.

665
00:46:27,800 --> 00:46:29,950
Tell them to bring up all of
the data lines right now.

666
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:31,310
Yes, hurry please.

667
00:46:31,719 --> 00:46:33,079
Hello Governor.

668
00:46:34,439 --> 00:46:37,070
Dr. Kuprin, we are trying
to restore communications.

669
00:46:53,035 --> 00:46:54,551
Don't hang up, I wanna talk to him.

670
00:46:54,762 --> 00:46:57,246
Orlo, something's happened,
we're declaring a state of emergency.

671
00:47:02,502 --> 00:47:04,548
I can't explain, do it now!

672
00:47:06,683 --> 00:47:09,447
Attention! Communications
will be restored in five seconds!

673
00:47:09,945 --> 00:47:11,070
We don't have any time!

674
00:47:12,023 --> 00:47:13,058
It's on, it's on!

675
00:47:13,084 --> 00:47:14,371
Communications are restored!

676
00:47:14,599 --> 00:47:17,607
Intercept Guardian missile target:
Henderson Air Force Base.

677
00:47:18,378 --> 00:47:19,884
Acknowledge message.

678
00:47:23,819 --> 00:47:24,967
Will you intercept?

679
00:47:27,020 --> 00:47:27,998
Ask it again.

680
00:47:32,546 --> 00:47:35,154
Dammit Colossus, answer me!
Will you intercept?

681
00:47:54,542 --> 00:47:56,900
Peterson. Get me the Governor again.

682
00:47:56,962 --> 00:47:58,036
Yes Sir.

683
00:48:13,109 --> 00:48:14,378
Mr. President...

684
00:48:16,741 --> 00:48:18,759
We were unable to restore...

685
00:48:19,869 --> 00:48:21,566
our transmission...

686
00:48:21,923 --> 00:48:23,306
in time to use...

687
00:48:23,739 --> 00:48:26,349
an anti-missile missile.

688
00:48:29,408 --> 00:48:31,666
The oil complex has been destroyed.

689
00:48:33,662 --> 00:48:35,037
The entire town,

690
00:48:36,408 --> 00:48:38,968
the entire population, wiped out.

691
00:48:40,049 --> 00:48:42,211
We need time to consider our position.

692
00:48:50,666 --> 00:48:52,213
What can I tell the people?

693
00:48:53,591 --> 00:48:55,080
Governor's on the line Sir.

694
00:48:56,121 --> 00:48:57,576
Tell him I'll talk to him later.

695
00:49:20,678 --> 00:49:21,994
Figures...

696
00:49:22,894 --> 00:49:25,366
It's the only phone
in the building not tapped.

697
00:49:26,099 --> 00:49:29,377
The only one not tied
directly into Colossus.

698
00:49:36,621 --> 00:49:38,544
May I make a suggestion Mr. President?

699
00:49:39,196 --> 00:49:40,858
I think it should be more
than a suggestion.

700
00:49:41,273 --> 00:49:43,752
Then let's try to get Kuprin
on the hot line.

701
00:49:45,004 --> 00:49:46,592
I think there's time for one last call,

702
00:49:46,618 --> 00:49:49,883
and he and I better meet somewhere
to discuss the situation.

703
00:49:50,842 --> 00:49:51,730
Get Kuprin,

704
00:49:51,756 --> 00:49:53,555
and get in touch with the networks.

705
00:49:59,502 --> 00:50:02,975
Ladies and gentlemen:
The President of the United States.

706
00:50:03,937 --> 00:50:06,550
Today at 8:30 A.M.
Eastern Standard Time,

707
00:50:06,600 --> 00:50:09,500
I issued an emergency warning
for the State of Texas,

708
00:50:09,550 --> 00:50:13,579
when a missile test-fired from one
of our own submarines, malfunctioned.

709
00:50:14,277 --> 00:50:17,829
You'll be glad to know that the interception
and safe destruction of the missile

710
00:50:17,855 --> 00:50:21,200
was handled entirely
by our defense complex, Colossus.

711
00:50:21,290 --> 00:50:24,372
The Soviet Union has just announced
that a large meteorite

712
00:50:24,406 --> 00:50:27,450
fell late this afternoon
in North-West Siberia.

713
00:50:27,500 --> 00:50:30,417
Official sources state that
the small town of Sayan-Sibirsk

714
00:50:30,481 --> 00:50:34,900
was completely destroyed, and that casualties
may add up to as many as six thousand.

715
00:50:34,950 --> 00:50:37,900
This has been a bulletin from
Armed Forces Radio in Rome.

716
00:50:40,279 --> 00:50:41,370
How's Washington?

717
00:50:42,315 --> 00:50:44,448
As well as can be expected.

718
00:50:45,581 --> 00:50:49,250
We'll be picking up Dr. Kuprin,
at the Piazza Cedra.

719
00:50:49,300 --> 00:50:50,300
Fine.

720
00:51:11,114 --> 00:51:13,250
Your Russian is much better
than you think.

721
00:51:13,300 --> 00:51:15,594
I think we better sit down because
we have a lot of work to discuss.

722
00:51:15,726 --> 00:51:17,600
Let's walk, it will be much safer.

723
00:51:57,930 --> 00:52:00,300
I didn't answer, I didn't know what to say.

724
00:52:01,865 --> 00:52:03,216
What can we say?

725
00:52:03,661 --> 00:52:05,225
Well, let's try something...

726
00:52:08,377 --> 00:52:09,581
Attention...

727
00:52:13,828 --> 00:52:16,200
Dr. Forbin is not available.

728
00:52:30,572 --> 00:52:32,600
Humans must have sleep.

729
00:52:35,280 --> 00:52:36,070
Damn.

730
00:52:36,568 --> 00:52:37,968
Forbin is exhausted.

731
00:52:43,514 --> 00:52:44,669
It knows...

732
00:52:49,465 --> 00:52:52,370
Forbin is in his quarters,
he is asleep.

733
00:52:52,407 --> 00:52:55,500
The human body requires
a certain amount of rest.

734
00:52:55,550 --> 00:52:57,016
Check units under...

735
00:53:02,116 --> 00:53:03,541
Tell it the truth.

736
00:53:07,281 --> 00:53:08,348
We'd better.

737
00:53:12,243 --> 00:53:15,040
Alright. Forbin is in Rome.

738
00:53:54,939 --> 00:53:56,185
They're still here...

739
00:54:09,261 --> 00:54:10,621
Yes I understand.

740
00:54:10,647 --> 00:54:11,845
Over and out.

741
00:55:06,784 --> 00:55:08,932
You have to come with me sir.

742
00:55:11,501 --> 00:55:12,667
What is this?

743
00:55:13,853 --> 00:55:15,400
- We have to hurry.
- Who are you?

744
00:55:15,453 --> 00:55:16,613
What's going on?

745
00:55:22,980 --> 00:55:23,980
Hurry!

746
00:55:55,253 --> 00:55:57,183
Dr. Forbin, we must hurry.
Let's go!

747
00:56:23,275 --> 00:56:25,730
What did the Russian agent say?

748
00:56:29,535 --> 00:56:31,890
Guardian and Colossus
ordered him killed.

749
00:56:31,939 --> 00:56:35,850
They... they threatened to vaporize Moscow
if our meeting wasn't stopped.

750
00:56:58,765 --> 00:57:01,840
- Surveillance!
- It's making you a prisoner.

751
00:57:06,027 --> 00:57:09,200
Well, I guess it er... doesn't trust me.

752
00:57:11,322 --> 00:57:13,717
But the damned thing still needs me.

753
00:57:14,581 --> 00:57:17,400
I guess Kuprin wasn't quite
as fortunate as that.

754
00:57:44,285 --> 00:57:45,979
Message acknowledged.

755
00:57:50,157 --> 00:57:51,981
The order will be obeyed.

756
00:58:00,151 --> 00:58:01,234
Everybody here?

757
00:58:01,855 --> 00:58:03,707
- All the departments.
- Good!

758
00:58:05,276 --> 00:58:07,925
Alright, let's... let's walk.

759
00:58:08,086 --> 00:58:10,845
Good idea, we can't afford
to take any chances.

760
00:58:11,392 --> 00:58:14,250
We can't be sure that
the complex itself hasn't been bugged,

761
00:58:14,307 --> 00:58:16,979
by our side, their side or whatever side.

762
00:58:17,264 --> 00:58:19,757
But there's no way
to get back inside the system.

763
00:58:20,653 --> 00:58:21,988
I won't accept that.

764
00:58:23,080 --> 00:58:24,432
Start right at the beginning.

765
00:58:24,905 --> 00:58:28,200
Down to the simplest component.
Every circuit, every design.

766
00:58:28,793 --> 00:58:29,941
Fisher?

767
00:58:30,178 --> 00:58:32,182
Well, why don't we try for an overload.

768
00:58:32,483 --> 00:58:34,291
Giving the system too many tasks.

769
00:58:35,079 --> 00:58:39,259
But it will take at least a few days
to compile and correlate all the data.

770
00:58:43,092 --> 00:58:44,900
This is the last time,

771
00:58:45,942 --> 00:58:48,553
that I'll be able to say anything
to any of you,

772
00:58:48,646 --> 00:58:50,781
without Colossus hearing
and analyzing every...

